  "output": "## Codebase shape\n\nThis is an async Python job-scraper/notifier (no frontend), so \"React re-renders\" doesn't apply — I'll flag the closest analog (a sequential-fetch \"waterfall\") instead. Findings below are grounded in what's actually in the repo, not generic advice.\n\n### 1. N+1 query pattern — `store.py:60-74` (`Store.diff`)\n\n```python\nfor job in jobs:\n    row = cur.execute(\"SELECT content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key = ?\", (job.key,)).fetchone()\n    if row is None:\n        new.append(job)\n        self._insert(cur, job, now)\n    ...\n```\n\nOne `SELECT` + one `INSERT`/`UPDATE` per job, in a loop. With Amazon/Microsoft/Netflix alone capable of returning thousands of rows per run, this is thousands of individual round-trips through SQLite's parser/planner even though it's local. Batch it:\n\n```python\ndef diff(self, jobs: list[Job]) -> tuple[list[Job], list[Job]]:\n    now = datetime.now(timezone.utc).isoformat(timespec=\"seconds\")\n    keys = [j.key for j in jobs]\n    existing = {}\n    for i in range(0, len(keys), 500):          # stay under SQLite's var limit\n        chunk = keys[i:i + 500]\n        q = f\"SELECT key, content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key IN ({','.join('?' * len(chunk))})\"\n        existing.update({r[\"key\"]: r[\"content_hash\"] for r in self.conn.execute(q, chunk)})\n\n    new, changed, inserts, updates, touches = [], [], [], [], []\n    for job in jobs:\n        prev_hash = existing.get(job.key)\n        row = {**job.to_row(), \"now\": now}\n        if prev_hash is None:\n            new.append(job); inserts.append(row)\n        elif prev_hash != row[\"content_hash\"]:\n            changed.append(job); updates.append(row)\n        else:\n            touches.append({\"key\": job.key, \"now\": now})\n\n    cur = self.conn.cursor()\n    if inserts:\n        cur.executemany(\"\"\"INSERT INTO jobs (key, source, company, external_id, title, url,\n             location, department, employment_type, posted_at, salary_range,\n             content_hash, first_seen, last_seen)\n           VALUES (:key,:source,:company,:external_id,:title,:url,:location,\n             :department,:employment_type,:posted_at,:salary_range,\n             :content_hash,:now,:now)\"\"\", inserts)\n    if updates:\n        cur.executemany(\"\"\"UPDATE jobs SET title=:title, url=:url, location=:location,\n             department=:department, employment_type=:employment_type,\n             posted_at=:posted_at, salary_range=:salary_range,\n             content_hash=:content_hash, last_seen=:now WHERE key=:key\"\"\", updates)\n    if touches:\n        cur.executemany(\"UPDATE jobs SET last_seen=:now WHERE key=:key\", touches)\n    self.conn.commit()\n    return new, changed\n```\nTurns O(N) queries into O(N/500 + 3) statements.\n\n### 2. Missing index — `store.py:111-119` (`added_since`)\n\nThe schema only indexes `company` (`store.py:27`), but `agent.py`'s `db-new` command runs `WHERE first_seen > ? ORDER BY first_seen, company, title` on every scan — a full table scan + sort as `jobs.db` grows across twice-daily runs. Add:\n\n```python\nCREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_jobs_first_seen ON jobs(first_seen);\n```\n\n### 3. Redundant computation — `filters.py:11-12, 21-27`\n\n`_compile()` recompiles every include/exclude regex **for every job**, inside `match()`, which itself runs once per job via the list comprehension in `filter_jobs` (`filters.py:49`). For N jobs and M keywords that's O(N×M) `re.compile` calls instead of O(M).\n\n```python\ndef filter_jobs(jobs: list[Job], rules: dict) -> list[Job]:\n    include = _compile(rules.get(\"include_keywords\") or [])\n    exclude = _compile(rules.get(\"exclude_keywords\") or [])\n    cutoff = ...\n    return [j for j in jobs if match(j, include=include, exclude=exclude, locations=..., cutoff=cutoff)]\n```\nand change `match()` to accept pre-compiled `list[re.Pattern]` instead of raw strings.\n\n### 4. Redundant computation — `models.py:66-69` + `store.py`\n\n`Job.content_hash` is a `@property` that does a `sha256` over a joined string on every access. `Store.diff` accesses it once for comparison (`store.py:67`) and then `_insert`/`_update` call `job.to_row()` (`store.py:71`) which recomputes it again — 2x per job. Cheap individually, but pure waste at scale. Since `to_row()` already returns a dict, just reuse the hash you already computed in `diff()` rather than letting `to_row()` recompute it (pass it in or set it on the row dict after the fact).\n\n### 5. Sequential-pagination waterfall (the \"re-render\" analog here) — `fetchers.py`\n\n`fetch_amazon`, `fetch_microsoft`, `fetch_netflix`, `fetch_google`, `fetch_twosigma`, `fetch_optiver` all page strictly sequentially, awaiting each page before requesting the next (e.g. `fetchers.py:729-737`, up to `max_pages=40`). For Amazon/Microsoft/Netflix, the **first response includes a `total` count** (`fetchers.py:466` shows this pattern already used in `fetch_workday`) — so pages 2..N don't need to wait on each other. Fetch page 1, compute page count, then fan out the rest under the existing semaphore:\n\n```python\nasync def fetch_amazon(client, source):\n    ...\n    first = await _get_json(client, url, params={**base, \"offset\": 0}, headers=...)\n    total = (first.get(\"hits\") or 0)\n    jobs = parse_amazon(company, first.get(\"jobs\") or [])\n    pages_needed = min(max_pages, -(-total // 10))\n    async def page(pg):\n        data = await _get_json(client, url, params={**base, \"offset\": pg * 10}, headers=...)\n        return parse_amazon(company, (data or {}).get(\"jobs\") or [])\n    rest = await asyncio.gather(*(page(pg) for pg in range(1, pages_needed)))\n    jobs += [j for batch in rest for j in batch]\n    return jobs\n```\nThis cuts wall-clock for large boards (Amazon/Microsoft configs default `max_pages=40`) from ~40 sequential round-trips to a handful of concurrent batches.\n\n### 6. Unnecessary memory retention — `fetchers.py` (`raw=j` in most parsers)\n\n`Job.raw` (`models.py:52`) stores the **entire** source payload for greenhouse/lever/ashby/smartrecruiters/recruitee/workable/workday parsers, but nothing reads `.raw` after construction — `to_row()` pops it before persisting (`models.py:73`), and `filters.py`/`notify.py` never touch it. For a company with thousands of Greenhouse listings, you're holding multiple KB × thousands of jobs in memory for the whole run for zero benefit. The `google`/`meta`/`microsoft`/`netflix`/`amazon` fetchers already trim this to just an id (e.g. `fetchers.py:247`, `532`) — apply the same trim to the rest, or drop the field to `raw=None` in `_simple()`'s parsers.\n\n### 7. Caching opportunity — no conditional GET / ETag support\n\nEvery run refetches full boards from scratch even when nothing changed (dedup happens *after* the fetch, in `Store.diff`). Several of these ATS APIs return `ETag`/`Last-Modified` on JSON responses. Worth caching per-source `(url, etag)` in the `meta` table (already used for the scan marker — `store.py:100-109`) and sending `If-None-Match`, short-circuiting on `304`. This is a bigger lift than the others and only pays off if the underlying APIs actually honor conditional headers — worth a quick probe before investing.\n\n---\n\n**Priority order**: #1 and #2 (store.py) are the highest-value, lowest-risk fixes since `jobs.db` grows every run. #5 (parallel pagination) gives the biggest wall-clock win if you're running large boards like Amazon/Microsoft on a schedule. #3/#4/#6 are cheap cleanups. #7 is a \"nice to have\" that needs verification against real API behavior before implementing.\n",
